subsidy trap
Cambridge, United States — No policy pits good economics so directly against good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become a core issue for three of the world's most important new leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi faces the challenge of reducing subsidies that are somewhat better than expected.
Conversely, Modi faces a situation that is even worse than expected, potentially jeopardizing the long-awaited World Trade Organization agreement.
And Jokowi faces an unclear situation.
In July, Sisi achieved a feat that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East could accomplish: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, increasing prices by 41-78%.
Surprisingly, there was little opposition to the protests.
The food subsidy program in Egypt consumes over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices remained at extremely low levels, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to reduce such subsidies often sparked unrest and even overthrew governments.
But Sisi's government seems to be making progress on this front as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy reductions, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year is 10% of GDP (it would be 14% without the subsidy cuts).
But hardly anyone expected Sisi, upon taking office in a turbulent political environment, to act more swiftly than Modi, who secured the prime ministerial position in India through an overwhelming democratic majority amid the pressing desire for comprehensive economic reform.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who took office in October, inherited fuel subsidies that amounted to $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), burdening the nation significantly.
The outgoing Suharto took a brave first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors suggested cutting the remaining subsidies, and he candidly stated his plan to phase them out over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, given that agricultural and energy markets approach perfect competition with numerous consumers on the demand side and numerous producers on the supply side.
In sectors where competition is imperfect, it is the government—not large private monopolies—that is the culprit.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For instance, income inequality and environmental externalities are the main reasons for government intervention.
The fact that food and fossil fuel subsidies often provoke sharp controversy is that they are frequently justified on environmental or equality grounds, yet they actually do little to achieve these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Only about 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest.
Only a far smaller fraction of global fossil fuel subsidies goes to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as the Modi government protecting agricultural subsidies in India demonstrates.
In fact, the Modi government rejected the WTO compromise, effectively undermining the most significant achievement of multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes allow producers to benefit at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; at other times, they enable consumers to benefit at the expense of producers, particularly in wealthy countries.
India's policies aim to do both.
As a result, India achieved a feat: rationing wheat to consumers at artificially low prices while facing excess supply, as farmers received higher prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs such as electricity, water, and fertilizer, at the expense of environmental degradation.)
) The government acquired large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, while a small portion allocated to consumers was both corrupt and ineffective in aiding the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since the rules cannot be permanently changed, Modi simply rejected the World Trade Organization's eagerly awaited Trade Facilitation Agreement.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are hard to reverse.
When global commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from the impact.
But people accustomed to government-set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument against implementing subsidies from the outset.
But this does not mean that maintaining subsidies once they are implemented is necessarily the wisest choice for astute politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could erupt.
Similarly, if the constantly widening gap eventually leads to higher retail prices, slow-moving leaders will not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, other more effective measures to support low-income households should be taken alongside the reduction of food and energy subsidies.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in implementing effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer policies like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries are forced to adjust only when budget crises hit, and they may lack the funds needed for transfers to cushion the pain.
Prudent politicians might implement unpopular adjustments from the start.
Jokowi and Sisi have adopted this approach.
And having won elections on a platform of market reforms, Modi is now lagging behind.
